Projections

Recall that calculating distances is not very meaningful using latitude and longitude as it will be in degrees.

  • first define the projection with the proj4 syntax
  • look at two: California Albers (Teale Projection) and UTM zone 11 (specific to SoCal)
proj_albers<-"+proj=aea +lat_1=34.0 +lat_2=40.5 +lon_0=-120.0 +x_0=0 +y_0=-4000000 +ellps=GRS80 +datum=NAD83 +units=km"
proj_utm11<-"+proj=utm +zone=11 +north +datum=WGS84 +units=km"

newcoords1<-project(as.matrix(cbind(pm_ca$longitude, pm_ca$latitude)), proj=proj_albers)
pm_ca$x_alb<-newcoords1[,1]
pm_ca$y_alb<-newcoords1[,2]


newcoords2<-project(as.matrix(cbind(pm_ca$longitude, pm_ca$latitude)), proj=proj_utm11)
pm_ca$x_utm<-newcoords2[,1]
pm_ca$y_utm<-newcoords2[,2]

We can make basic but informative exploratory maps with geoR objects

# Plotting geoR objects as point data with different colour ramps 
points(lpm_geo,cex.max=0.8,col=gray(seq(1, 0.1, l=100)), pt.div="equal")
# Add state boundaries to geoR plots
map("state",add=TRUE)

# adding labels, colours, gradients
points(lpm_geo,cex.max=0.9,col= colorRampPalette(c("darkblue", "white", "darkred"))(20), pt.divide="equal",main=" logPM2.5 concentrations (ug/m3)",xlab="Longitude",ylab="Latitude")
map("state",add=TRUE)

# colours and sizes
points(lpm_geo,cex.max=0.9, pt.divide="quartiles", main="PM2.5 concentrations", xlab="Longitude",ylab="Latitude")
map("state",add=TRUE)

# add crude legend
points(lpm_geo,col= rev(heat.colors(10)), x.leg= -125, y.leg=37, pt.divide="quintiles", main="PM2.5 concentrations (ug/m3)", xlab="Longitude",ylab="Latitude")
map("state",add=TRUE)

# subset geodata to look at a particular region

lpm_geo_ss<-subset(lpm_geo,longitude> -120  & latitude<42)
points(lpm_geo_ss,col= rev(heat.colors(20)), pt.div="equal", main="PM2.5 concentrations (ug/m3)", xlab="Longitude",ylab="Latitude")
map("state",add=TRUE)

Empirical Semivariograms

We will build empirical semivariograms including cloud, bin, boxplot bin

  • use Albers projection so distances are in km
  • semivariogram cloud plots semivariance at all pairwise distances
  • binned semivariogram averages semivariances by distance bins. The components of the binned semivariogram are distance range (min, max) and number of bins.
  • binned semivariogram boxplots can be informative to see how much data are in each bin.
  • the Cressie-Hawkins robust estimate of semivariance is tuned to deal with outliers and is often preferred. Its effect is really clear in the boxplot semivariograms.
# cloud semivariogram (all pairwise points)
vario1<-variog(lpm_geo_alb,option="cloud")
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
vario1$max.dist
## [1] 1187.489
plot(vario1,xlab="Distance (h), km")

# binned semivariogram
vario2<-variog(lpm_geo_alb,uvec=seq(0,vario1$max.dist,l=15),option="bin")
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
plot(vario2,xlab="Distance (h), km")

# shorter maximum distance more bins
vario3<-variog(lpm_geo_alb,uvec=seq(0,800,l=20),option="bin")
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
plot(vario3,xlab="Distance (h), km")

# shorter yet
vario3b<-variog(lpm_geo_alb,uvec=seq(0,200,l=15),option="bin")
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
plot(vario3b,xlab="Distance (h), km")

# boxplots
vario4<-variog(lpm_geo_alb,uvec=seq(0,vario1$max.dist,l=20),bin.cloud=T)
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
plot(vario4,bin.cloud=T,xlab="Bin")

vario4b<-variog(lpm_geo_alb,uvec=seq(0,200,l=20),bin.cloud=T)
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
plot(vario4b,bin.cloud=T,xlab="Bin")

# Robust estimator "modulus" is preferred
vario2m<-variog(lpm_geo_alb,uvec=seq(0,200,l=12),option="bin",estimator.type="modulus")
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
plot(vario2m,xlab="Distance (h), km")

vario4m<-variog(lpm_geo_alb,uvec=seq(0,200,l=20),bin.cloud=T,estimator.type="modulus")
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
plot(vario4m,bin.cloud=T,xlab="Distance (h), km")

Theoretical semivariograms by curve fitting

  • We use the eyeball method to fit some theoretical semivariograms to our empirical data
  • It is best to do this with the binned semivarigrams (robust estimator)
  • Using the equations from class we will fit the exponential and spherical functions with our best guesses for the nugget, sill and range
  • Curve fitting can generally be done using the curve() function. You need to supply the equation, the range in x that you want to plot (min, max distance), and any other options such as y limits, colors, titles, etc.
# Exponential

plot(vario2m,xlab="Distance (h)")
curve(0.1+0.5*(1-exp(-x/100)),from = 0 , to=vario2m$max.dist, col="red",ylab="Semivariance", xlab="Distance (h)",ylim=c(0,0.6),add=T)

# Spherical
plot(vario2m,xlab="Distance (h)")
curve(0.05+0.5*(1.5*(x/200)-0.5*(x/200)^3),from = 0 , col="blue",to=vario2m$max.dist, ylab="Semivariance", xlab="Distance (h)",add=T)

Anisotropy

  • If we look at the semivariogram from different angles we can see if we are violating stationarity by direction
  • variog4 in the geoR library lets us visualize the directional differences
# Exploring anisotropy (introduction for next lecture)

vario.dir<-variog4(lpm_geo_alb,uvec=seq(0,800,l=25),option="bin",estimator.type="modulus")
## variog: computing variogram for direction = 0 degrees (0 radians)
##         tolerance angle = 22.5 degrees (0.393 radians)
## variog: computing variogram for direction = 45 degrees (0.785 radians)
##         tolerance angle = 22.5 degrees (0.393 radians)
## variog: computing variogram for direction = 90 degrees (1.571 radians)
##         tolerance angle = 22.5 degrees (0.393 radians)
## variog: computing variogram for direction = 135 degrees (2.356 radians)
##         tolerance angle = 22.5 degrees (0.393 radians)
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
plot(vario.dir)

vario.dir2<-variog4(lpm_geo_alb,uvec=seq(0,200,l=15),option="bin",estimator.type="modulus")
## variog: computing variogram for direction = 0 degrees (0 radians)
##         tolerance angle = 22.5 degrees (0.393 radians)
## variog: computing variogram for direction = 45 degrees (0.785 radians)
##         tolerance angle = 22.5 degrees (0.393 radians)
## variog: computing variogram for direction = 90 degrees (1.571 radians)
##         tolerance angle = 22.5 degrees (0.393 radians)
## variog: computing variogram for direction = 135 degrees (2.356 radians)
##         tolerance angle = 22.5 degrees (0.393 radians)
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
plot(vario.dir2)
